│ `loop-vectorize` pass is crashing with an assertion failure, │
│ `!verifyFunction(...)`, indicating that it has generated     │
│ malformed LLVM IR. The specific error, \"Instruction does    │
│ not dominate all uses!\", points to a dominance problem      │
│ where an instruction's definition does not properly dominate │
│ one of its uses. This typically happens when an instruction  │
│ is placed in a basic block that is not an ancestor of all    │
│ the blocks where its result is used.\n\nThe crash occurs     │
│ when vectorizing a loop containing a recurrence PHI node     │
│ where the incoming value from the loop's backedge is         │
│ loop-invariant. In the provided reproducer, the PHI node     │
│ is:\n`%for = phi i8 [ %for.start, %entry ], [ %for.next,     │
│ %loop ]`\nwhere `%for.next` is defined as `and i8            │
│ %for.start, -1`. Since `%for.start` is a loop-invariant      │
│ function argument, `%for.next` is also                       │
│ loop-invariant.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` │
│ log shows that the Scalar Evolution (SCEV) analysis          │
│ correctly identifies the recurrence variable `%for` as       │
│ loop-invariant:\n`%for = phi i8 [ %for.start, %entry ], [    │
│ %for.next, %loop ] --> %for.start ... LoopDispositions: {    │
│ %loop: Invariant }`\n\nThis is a crucial piece of            │
│ information. The loop vectorizer should recognize that this  │
│ is not a true recurrence (where the value in one iteration   │
│ depends on the value from the previous iteration), but       │
│ rather a value that is recomputed from loop-invariant        │
│ sources in every iteration.\n\nThe crash message pinpoints   │
│ the problem:\n`Instruction does not dominate all             │
│ uses!`\n`%broadcast.splat2 = shufflevector                   │
│ ...`\n`%vector.recur = phi <4 x i8> [ %vector.recur.init,    │
│ %vector.ph ], [ %broadcast.splat2, %vector.body ]`\n\nThis   │
│ tells us that `%broadcast.splat2`, which is the vectorized   │
│ value for the recurrence update, is used in the              │
│ `%vector.recur` PHI node in the `vector.body` block, but it  │
│ is not defined in a block that dominates                     │
│ `vector.body`.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root     │
│ cause lies in how the `LoopVectorize` pass handles this      │
│ specific type of \"invariant\" recurrence.\n\n1.             │
│ **Recurrence Analysis**: The vectorizer identifies `%for` as │
│ a recurrence. It correctly determines that the value for the │
│ next iteration, `%for.next`, is loop-invariant.\n2.  **VPlan │
│ Construction**: A `VPlan` (Vectorization Plan) is built to   │
│ represent the vectorized loop. For the recurrence, a         │
│ `VPRecipe` is created for `%for.next`.\n3.  **Sinking        │
│ Logic**: During the transformation from VPlan to LLVM IR,    │
│ the vectorizer tries to sink loop-invariant instructions out │
│ of the loop into the preheader to avoid recomputing them in  │
│ every iteration. This is generally a good optimization.\n4.  │
│ **The Bug**: The logic for sinking has a flaw. It decides to │
│ sink the computation of `%for.next` (and its vectorized      │
│ equivalent, `%broadcast.splat2`) into the loop's preheader   │
│ (`vector.ph`). However, the value produced by this sunk      │
│ instruction is needed for the recurrence PHI node            │
│ (`%vector.recur`) inside the vectorized loop body            │
│ (`vector.body`). The preheader does not dominate the loop    │
│ body's backedge source. The value is needed for the `[       │
│ %broadcast.splat2, %vector.body ]` incoming edge of the PHI, │
│ but `%broadcast.splat2` is in the preheader. The correct     │
│ location for `%broadcast.splat2` would be inside             │
│ `vector.body`, right before the backedge branch.\n\nThe      │
│ sinking decision is made in `LoopVectorize.cpp` within the   │
│ `LoopVectorizePass::processLoop` function, specifically when │
│ handling recipes for the vectorized loop. The check that     │
│ determines if an instruction can be sunk is too aggressive   │
│ for this corner case. It fails to recognize that even though │
│ the recurrence update is loop-invariant, it's still part of  │
│ the data flow *within* the loop structure for the recurrence │
│ PHI, and thus cannot be hoisted to the preheader.\n\n### 4.  │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to prevent the sinking  │
│ of recurrence-related instructions that are used by a PHI    │
│ node within the loop. The existing sinking logic already has │
│ a check to avoid sinking instructions that are part of a     │
│ reduction. A similar check needs to be added for             │
│ recurrences.\n\nThe edit is in                               │
│ `LoopVectorizePass::processLoop`, where the code iterates    │
│ through `VPRecipe`s and decides whether to sink them. The    │
│ proposed change is to add                                    │
│ `isa<VPWidenRecurrencePHIRecipe>(R)` to the condition that   │
│ prevents sinking.\n\n**File**:                               │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`\n**Origina │
│ l Lines (8901-8902)**:\n```cpp\n                             │
│ isa<VPWidenSelectRecipe>(R) || isa<VPBlendRecipe>(R) ||\n    │
│ isa<VPPredInstPHIRecipe>(R))\n```\n\n**Proposed              │
│ Change**:\n```cpp\n                                          │
│ isa<VPWidenRecurrencePHIRecipe>(R) ||                        │
│ isa<VPWidenSelectRecipe>(R) ||\n                             │
│ isa<VPBlendRecipe>(R) ||                                     │
│ isa<VPPredInstPHIRecipe>(R))\n```\nThis adds the necessary   │
│ check for recurrence PHI recipes.\n\n### 5.                  │
│ Conclusion\n\nThe assertion failure is due to incorrect      │
│ sinking of a loop-invariant instruction that serves as the   │
│ update value for a recurrence PHI. By hoisting the           │
│ instruction to the loop preheader, the vectorizer breaks the │
│ dominance property required for valid LLVM IR.\n\nThe        │
│ proposed fix corrects this by refining the sinking logic. It │
│ adds a check to prevent instructions that are part of a      │
│ recurrence (`VPWidenRecurrencePHIRecipe`) from being sunk.   │
│ This ensures the instruction remains inside the vectorized   │
│ loop body, where it correctly dominates its use in the       │
│ recurrence PHI, thus resolving the crash and producing valid │
│ code."                                                       │
│ }                                                            │
